'''Keanolani''' (July 7, 1847 – June 30, 1902) was a Hawaiian chiefess ([[aliʻi]]) of the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]]. She was the illegitimate daughter of [[Abigail Maheha]] and King [[Kamehameha V]], who reigned from 1863 to 1872, and was born during a liaison between the two when they were students at the [[Royal School (Hawaii)|Chiefs' Children's School]] (later renamed the Royal School), a boarding school run by American missionaries for students of Hawaiian royal descent. Keanolani was raised by her father's half-sister [[Keʻelikōlani]]. Her illegitimate birth and unacknowledged parentage prevented her from succeeding to the Hawaiian throne when her father died without naming an heir, thus ending the reign of the [[House of Kamehameha]]. In 1873, she became a mistress of her uncle by marriage [[William Hoapili Kaʻauwai]]. In 1874, she became a supporter of the newly elected [[House of Kalākaua]]. She married and left descendants. Her name is also often spelled as '''Keano''' or '''Keanu'''. In one source, she is named as '''Keauoʻokalau'''.{{sfn|Muir|1952|page=10}}

== Life ==
[[File:Prince Lot Kapuaiwa (PP-97-9-007).jpg|thumb|left|150px|Prince [[Lot Kapuāiwa]], {{circa|1850}}]]
Keanolani was born July 7, 1847, on the island of [[Kauai|Kauaʻi]].{{sfn|Kaomea|2014|page=140}} Her birth occurred five months after her mother, thirteen-year-old [[Abigail Maheha]], had an arranged marriage to a commoner named Keaupuni, an expelled student from [[Lahainaluna Seminary]] and servant of her ''[[hānai]]'' (informally adopted) mother, Governess [[Kekauʻōnohi]] of Kauaʻi. Through Maheha, Keanolani was the granddaughter of High Chief Namaile and High Chiefess [[Kuini Liliha]], who was the [[Governors of Oahu|Royal Governor of Oʻahu]] from 1829 to 1831 and a political adversary of [[Kaʻahumanu|Queen Kaʻahumanu]], the [[Kuhina Nui]] (premier) during the reigns of [[Kamehameha II]] and [[Kamehameha III]].{{sfn|McKinzie|1983|pages=41–42}}{{sfn|Kam|2017|pages=70–72}}{{sfn|Cooke|Cooke|1937|pages=279–280}} Maheha was a former student at the [[Royal School (Hawaii)|Chiefs' Children's School]], later renamed the Royal School, a boarding school run by American missionaries [[Amos Starr Cooke]] and his wife Juliette Montague Cooke for students of Hawaiian royal descent. She was declared eligible for the throne of the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]] by King Kamehameha III.<ref name="Polynesian1844">{{cite news|title=Princes and Chiefs eligible to be Rulers|newspaper=The Polynesian|location=Honolulu|date=July 20, 1844|volume=1|issue=9|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1844-07-20/ed-1/seq-1/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222092650/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1844-07-20/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=December 22, 2015|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Van Dyke|2008|page=364}}{{sfn|Kaomea|2014|page=125}} However, the thirteen-year-old Maheha had left the school at the insistence of her teachers, and was married off to Keaupuni to cover an unexpected pregnancy.{{sfn|Kam|2017|pages=70–72}}{{sfn|Kaomea|2014|pages=139–144}} Keaupuni was not the biological father of the baby, as was later attested by Mele, a witness in the 1855 divorce suit between him and Maheha.{{sfn|Kam|2017|pages=70–72}}

Her father was not officially identified. However, during and after her lifetime, speculation has focused on two princes of the [[Kamehameha dynasty]]: the seventeen-year-old [[Moses Kekūāiwa]], who was the eldest boy at the Royal School, or his sixteen-year-old brother Lot Kapuāiwa, who later became King [[Kamehameha V]]. Evidence points toward Lot because Moses was expelled from the school two days before Maheha. He had also financially supported Maheha's husband Keaupuni. The entries from the period after September 1, 1845, were also torn out of Lot's school journal.{{sfn|Kam|2017|pages=70–72}}{{sfn|Kaomea|2014|pages=139–144}}{{sfn|Walker|Ahlo|Johnson|2000|page=78}}<ref name="Keawe1903">{{cite news|last=Keawe|first=J. H.|title=He Kamehameha Oiaio Oia|newspaper=Ka Nupepa Kuokoa|location=Honolulu|date=July 31, 1903|volume=XLI|issue=31|page=1|url=https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2017/03/12/samuela-kekuiapoiwa-1903/#more-33782|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716060307/https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2017/03/12/samuela-kekuiapoiwa-1903/#more-33782|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She was raised by Princess [[Keʻelikōlani|Ruth Keʻelikōlani]], her namesake and the half-sister of Kamehameha V.<ref name="Keanolani" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Hala ia Pua Alii o Ka Aina – Make O Keanu Ma Kapakai O Waikiki|newspaper=Ka Nupepa Kuokoa|location=Honolulu|date=July 4, 1902|volume=XL|issue=27|page=1|url=https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2013/04/16/keanu-daughter-of-kamehameha-v-and-keelikolani-passes-1902/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716060207/https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2013/04/16/keanu-daughter-of-kamehameha-v-and-keelikolani-passes-1902/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kamehameha V reigned from 1863 to his death on December 11, 1872, without acknowledging his daughter or naming an heir to the throne, and was succeeded by his cousin [[Lunalilo]].{{sfn|Kanahele|1999|pages=263–267}}{{sfn|Van Dyke|2008|page=93}} Keanolani would not have been eligible to succeed Kamehameha V since the [[1864 Constitution of the Kingdom of Hawaii|Hawaiian constitution]] only permitted succession through legitimate lines. Similarly, [[Albert Kūnuiākea]], the illegitimate son of Kamehameha III, had not been considered for the throne in 1854.{{sfn|Haley|2014|pages=103–104, 172}}

[[File:Hoapili Kaauwai and Kiliwehi.jpg|thumb|Keaonolani became the mistress of her uncle by marriage [[William Hoapili Kaʻauwai]] (left), who was initially married to her half-aunt [[Kiliwehi]] (right).]]
While still married to her first husband Lihilihi, Keanolani became the mistress of [[William Hoapili Kaʻauwai]], an [[Church of Hawaii|Anglican]] chaplain and a high chief of [[Maui]]an descent who had divorced her half-aunt [[Kiliwehi]] in 1872. During this period, Hoapili and Keanolani were partisans of King [[Kalākaua]], who had been elected as monarch in 1874 after the death of King Lunalilo. Hoapili was promised the position of Royal Chamberlain in the new ruling household.{{sfn|Muir|1952|pages=5–13}}{{sfn|Kaeo|Queen Emma|1976|pages=112–114}} [[Queen Emma of Hawaii|Queen Emma]], the widow of [[Kamehameha IV]] and former patron of Hoapili and Kiliwehi, noted the illicit affair in her letters in 1873. Commenting on September 20, Emma wrote, "Hoapili and Keano are at David’s [Kalākaua's] Hamohamo. It is said she is with child by him again." Later, on September 26, she noted, "Keano was here last evening and appeared to be looking thick round the waist. She reports Kiliwehi recovering under Dr. [[Ferdinand William Hutchison|Hutchison]]’s treatment...."{{sfn|Kaeo|Queen Emma|1976|pages=112–114}} Keanolani had an illegitimate son which she named William Hoapili Kaʻauwai II, born on January 31, 1874. The elder Hoapili died on March 30, 1874.{{sfn|Muir|1952|pages=5–13}}<ref name="Hoapili"/>

Keanolani became a friend of [[Queen Kapiolani|Queen Kapiʻolani]], the wife of King Kalākaua. Few details exist on her life after this point until her death. In later life, she lived on the premises of Pualeilani, the [[Waikīkī]] residence of the queen. She continued living at Pualeilani when her nephews Princes [[David Kawānanakoa]] and [[Jonah Kūhiō Kalanianaʻole]] inherited the property.<ref name="Keanolani" /> At this point, the Hawaiian monarchy had been [[Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii|overthrown in 1893]] and the islands subsequently annexed by the United States in 1898. Despite this, her rank was acknowledged during the birthday reception of the former Queen [[Liliʻuokalani]] in 1901. The press initially described her as "old and mentally infirm" but also commented favorably on her noble bearing and knowledge of court etiquette.<ref name="1901Birthday">{{cite news|title=Royal Luaus Given By Liliuokalani|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=September 3, 1901|volume=|issue=|pages=9, 13|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1901-09-03/ed-1/seq-9/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716111726/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1901-09-03/ed-1/seq-9/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Royal Luaus Given By Liliuokalani|newspaper=The Hawaiian Gazette|location=Honolulu|date=September 3, 1901|volume=|issue=|page=5|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1901-09-03/ed1/seq-5/}}</ref> It was reported that she "swept majestically along amongst the throng as if she were a reigning queen"<ref name="Keanolani" /> and "greeted the Queen as one high chieftess [sic] to another."<ref name="1901Birthday" />

Keanolani died on June 30, 1902, while bathing at the beaches of Waikīkī near Pualeilani. She died on the beach after a swim in the ocean.<ref name="Keanolani">{{cite news|title=Keanu Dies On The Sea Shore|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=July 1, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1902-07-01/ed-1/seq-2/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716082343/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1902-07-01/ed-1/seq-2/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Keanu Dies On The Sea Shore|newspaper=The Hawaiian Gazette|location=Honolulu|date=July 1, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=4|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1902-07-01/ed-1/seq-4/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716082413/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1902-07-01/ed-1/seq-4/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Death Of A Chiefess – Reputed Daughter Of Kamehameha Dead|newspaper=The Hawaiian Star|location=Honolulu|date=June 30, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015415/1902-06-30/ed-1/seq-1/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716082321/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015415/1902-06-30/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Death Of A Chiefess – Apoplexy the Cause While Bathing in the Sea at Waikiki|newspaper=The Independent|location=Honolulu|date=July 2, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=5|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1902-07-02/ed-1/seq-5/|access-date=July 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723212447/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1902-07-02/ed-1/seq-5/|archive-date=July 23, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The cause of death was reported as [[apoplexy]] in her obituaries due to the discoloration of her face, and the coroner ruled that it was due to "fatty degeneration of the heart."<ref name="Keanolani" /><ref name="Coroner">{{cite news|title=Had Heart Disease|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=July 2, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=5|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1902-07-02/ed-1/seq-5/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165626/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1902-07-02/ed-1/seq-5/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Had Heart Disease|newspaper=The Hawaiian Gazette|location=Honolulu|date=July 5, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=6|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1902-07-04/ed-1/seq-6/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112030/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1902-07-04/ed-1/seq-6/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She died [[intestate]] and her daughter Kahaina petitioned to be appointed administratrix of the estate, which was valued at $2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court Notes|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=July 19, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=12|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1902-07-19/ed-1/seq-12/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112057/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1902-07-19/ed-1/seq-12/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=In the Matter of the Estate of Keanu|newspaper=Evening Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=July 18, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=8|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016413/1902-07-18/ed-1/seq-8/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165612/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016413/1902-07-18/ed-1/seq-8/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Local And General News|newspaper=The Independent|location=Honolulu|date=July 19, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1902-07-19/ed-1/seq-3/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112015/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1902-07-19/ed-1/seq-3/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After the autopsy, her remains laid in state at the bungalow of Pualeilani on July 1. The funeral service on the next day was conducted by Reverend [[Henry Hodges Parker]], the pastor of [[Kawaiahaʻo Church]]. Her pallbearers included her son Hoapili Kaʻauwai II and her maternal uncle Palekaluhi. Her body was laid to rest at the Kawaiahaʻo Cemetery.<ref name="Keanolani" />

== Marriage and descendants ==
Keanolani had a number of children. Her first husband was Lihilihi, from Kauaʻi, with whom she had a son named Samuela Kekuiapoiwa, who died on June 23, 1903.<ref name="Keawe1903" />{{sfn|McKinzie|1983|page=43}}

While still married to Lihilihi, Keanolani had an illegitimate son William Hoapili Kaʻauwai II, born on January 31, 1874, with her uncle by marriage [[William Hoapili Kaʻauwai]].{{sfn|Muir|1952|pages=5–13}}<ref name="Hoapili">{{harvnb|McKinzie|1983|pages=43, 49}}; {{cite news|title=Mookuauhau Alii – Na Iwikuamoo o Hawaii Nei Mai Kahiko Mai|newspaper=Ka Makaainana|location=Honolulu|date=August 10, 1896|volume=VI|issue=6|page=2|url=http://nupepa.org/gsdl2.5/cgi-bin/nupepa?e=d-0nupepa--00-0-0--010---4----prev-mid--0-1l--1en-Zz-1--en-20-about--20-00031-0000utfZz-8-00-0003-1-0000utfZz-8-00&cl=CL1.19.5&d=HASH34acc63dc93bb3624f18c7.2&gg=text|accessdate=September 26, 2016}}</ref>

She later divorced Lihilihi at the command of her aunt Keʻelikōlani.<ref name="Keawe1903" /><ref>{{cite web|author=Hawaiʻi State Archives|year=2006|title=Keano divorce record|website=Fifth Circuit Court. Indexes. Divorces: 1852 to 1899|volume=|page=3|via=Ulukau, the Hawaiian Electronic Library|url=http://ulukau.org/algene/cgi-bin/algene?e=d-001off-algene--00CL1%2e18--2----0--010---4-------0-1l--10en-Zz-1---20-about---00-1-1-00-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&d=18-000004&gg=|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> From her next marriage to Kamali, she had three children including Lot Kapuāiwa Kamehameha (1883/1884–1917), who died age 33,<ref>{{cite news|title=Member Of Royalty Summoned By Death|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=June 14, 1917|volume=|issue=|page=5|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-06-14/ed-2/seq-5/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112017/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-06-14/ed-2/seq-5/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Died|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=June 14, 1917|volume=|issue=|page=7|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-06-14/ed-2/seq-7/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716111835/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82014682/1917-06-14/ed-2/seq-7/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Keōpūolani,<ref name="Keawe1903" /> and Olga Keahikuni Kekauʻōnohi (1888/1889–1907), who died aged 18.<ref>{{cite news|title=Young Chiefess Dies Last Night|newspaper=The Hawaiian Star|location=Honolulu|date=May 8, 1907|volume=|issue=|page=8|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015415/1907-05-08/ed-1/seq-8/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112053/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015415/1907-05-08/ed-1/seq-8/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Young Chiefess Dies After Long Illness|newspaper=Evening Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=May 8, 1907|volume=|issue=|page=2|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016413/1907-05-08/ed-1/seq-2/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165623/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016413/1907-05-08/ed-1/seq-2/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Local Brevities|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=May 9, 1907|volume=|issue=|page=9|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1907-05-09/ed-1/seq-9/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112049/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1907-05-09/ed-1/seq-9/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Her obituary in 1902 reported, "Several years ago her husband [Kamali] went away into the mountains and nothing more was heard of him."<ref name="Keanolani" />

Another daughter mentioned in the sources was Kahaina, who petitioned to be appointed administratrix of her mother's estate after her death.<ref name="Estate">{{cite news|title=Local And General News|newspaper=The Independent|location=Honolulu|date=July 19, 1902|volume=|issue=|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1902-07-19/ed-1/seq-3/|access-date=July 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112015/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1902-07-19/ed-1/seq-3/|archive-date=July 16, 2018|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

